Si potas avelli Circensibus] The Ludi Circenses, or Magni, took place annually, and were of the highest antiquity, having been first celebrated by Romulus, as the tradition went, cn the occasion oi the rape of the Sabine women, under the name of Consuaha. They con- sisted of horse, chariat, and foot races, sham fights, both land and water, wrestling, boxing, and fighting with beasts, as well as ieats of horsemanship such as are witnessed in modern circuses. These were performed in the Circus Maximus, the vast building erected, according to tradition, by Tarquinius Priscus between the Aventina and Palatina hills. The passion of the Romans for these exhibitions was very strong. Juvenal has many allusione to this. ‘Avelli' is in themid- dle voice.
